body:
Yes, that is because currently each InferenceSession only has one cuda compute stream in it and so when you run on two different threads using the same session instance, the compute happens only on one stream and this explains the phenomenon you are seeing. We have a backlog item to use one compute stream per-thread within the same session instance and so both calls can run independently.

When you use one session per-thread you don't see this because each session is using its own compute stream now.

Linking a similar issue: https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/11047

CC: @pranavsharma @RyanUnderhill
thx for your reply, but i am using the cpu ep，is it same as cuda ep？
the result of perf show MlasGemmFloatKernelFma3 takes about 13% of cpu，maybe its performance related to multithread？ my intraopnums is set to one and use sequential executor
but when i tracing the session::run, i find the ops cost few time, but session::run itself costs a lof of time

> thx for your reply, but i am using the cpu ep，is it same as cuda ep？

Oh I am sorry - I had misunderstood this to be the CUDA EP. Can you maybe share some code around how the threadpool has been configured ?

Can you please provide the code you're using to create and run the sessions, and measure performance, so that the issue can be reproduced?

The session Run is stateless, so there aren't many places where two sessions could potentially block each other.
